On a cppreference page you see two numbered lines:

```cpp
(1) constexpr const T& min( const T& a, const T& b );
(2) constexpr T  min( std::initializer_list<T> ilist );
```

What does the numbering mean?

Suppose you look up `std::min` on cppreference. Its description says: `Returns the smaller of the two values. If the values are equivalent, returns a`. Based on that signature, what does this program print?

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <algorithm>

int main()
{
    std::cout << std::min(7, 3) << ' ' << std::min(4, 4) << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```

What is the bug here?

```cpp
#include <iostream>
#include <algorithm>

int main()
{
    // Trying to call std::min(int, int) — the two-argument overload.
    std::cout << std::min({ 7 }) << '\n';
    return 0;
}
```
